{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MBLuuadnsXddcRX4heB6Dv","type":"tool_result","content":"![critical](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/critical.svg)\n\nThis is a major version bump for `dotenv` from v9.0.2 to v17.3.1, introduced via the `@remotion/cli` dependency update. Major version updates often contain breaking changes, which contradicts the PR description's claim of 'no breaking changes'. This significant jump requires careful manual verification to ensure compatibility and prevent unexpected issues.\n![high](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/high-priority.svg)\n\nThis is a major version bump for `es-module-lexer` from v1.7.0 to v2.0.0, introduced via the `webpack` dependency update. Major version updates can introduce breaking changes, which contradicts the PR description's claim of only including patch updates. This should be carefully reviewed.\n![high](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/high-priority.svg)\n\nThis is a significant update for `react-refresh` from v0.9.0 to v0.18.0. For packages in the `0.x` version range, even minor version bumps can introduce breaking changes according to semantic versioning. This update, brought in by `@remotion/bundler`, contradicts the PR's claim of having no breaking changes and should be tested carefully.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"98205e1a-a018-40f3-839d-6f95fb6c6bb7","uuid":"c31f5897-e032-49eb-8905-114190996726","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"![critical](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/critical.svg)\n\nThis is a major version bump for `dotenv` from v9.0.2 to v17.3.1, introduced via the `@remotion/cli` dependency update. Major version updates often contain breaking changes, which contradicts the PR description's claim of 'no breaking changes'. This significant jump requires careful manual verification to ensure compatibility and prevent unexpected issues.\n![high](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/high-priority.svg)\n\nThis is a major version bump for `es-module-lexer` from v1.7.0 to v2.0.0, introduced via the `webpack` dependency update. Major version updates can introduce breaking changes, which contradicts the PR description's claim of only including patch updates. This should be carefully reviewed.\n![high](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/high-priority.svg)\n\nThis is a significant update for `react-refresh` from v0.9.0 to v0.18.0. For packages in the `0.x` version range, even minor version bumps can introduce breaking changes according to semantic versioning. This update, brought in by `@remotion/bundler`, contradicts the PR's claim of having no breaking changes and should be tested carefully.","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Kt56a1dk8zibDCEqTaEkgT","type":"tool_result","content":"![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)\n\nFor better maintainability and to ensure these TypeScript-specific rules only apply to TypeScript files, it's a good practice to explicitly scope this configuration block to `.ts` and `.tsx` files using the `files` property. While the current setup might work due to how `typescript-eslint` configs are structured, being explicit prevents unexpected behavior if JavaScript files are added to the project later.\n\n```javascript\n  {\n    files: ['**/*.ts', '**/*.tsx'],\n    rules: {\n      // Allow explicit any where needed (tighten later)\n      \"@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any\": \"warn\",\n      // Allow unused vars prefixed with _\n      \"@typescript-eslint/no-unused-vars\": [\n        \"error\",\n        { argsIgnorePattern: \"^_\", varsIgnorePattern: \"^_\" },\n      ],\n    },\n  },\n```\n![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)\n\nThis variable `remaining` is declared but never used. It can be removed.\n\nAdditionally, it seems the implementation of `splitOnClauses` doesn't fully match its intent. It checks for clause delimiters with `clausePattern` but then proceeds to split the sentence based on `MAX_CAPTION_LENGTH` regardless of where the clauses are. This might lead to captions being split in awkward places. You might want to refactor this to actually split on the detected clause delimiters.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"98205e1a-a018-40f3-839d-6f95fb6c6bb7","uuid":"77a6bbf8-4e23-4106-9890-d2ad90a3552e","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)\n\nFor better maintainability and to ensure these TypeScript-specific rules only apply to TypeScript files, it's a good practice to explicitly scope this configuration block to `.ts` and `.tsx` files using the `files` property. While the current setup might work due to how `typescript-eslint` configs are structured, being explicit prevents unexpected behavior if JavaScript files are added to the project later.\n\n```javascript\n  {\n    files: ['**/*.ts', '**/*.tsx'],\n    rules: {\n      // Allow explicit any where needed (tighten later)\n      \"@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any\": \"warn\",\n      // Allow unused vars prefixed with _\n      \"@typescript-eslint/no-unused-vars\": [\n        \"error\",\n        { argsIgnorePattern: \"^_\", varsIgnorePattern: \"^_\" },\n      ],\n    },\n  },\n```\n![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)\n\nThis variable `remaining` is declared but never used. It can be removed.\n\nAdditionally, it seems the implementation of `splitOnClauses` doesn't fully match its intent. It checks for clause delimiters with `clausePattern` but then proceeds to split the sentence based on `MAX_CAPTION_LENGTH` regardless of where the clauses are. This might lead to captions being split in awkward places. You might want to refactor this to actually split on the detected clause delimiters.","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
